    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-05-04T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-05-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="732"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d732">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.113/1604</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 3871</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-05-04">May 4,
                            1935</date>.<lb/>[Received May 15.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to the Legation’s despatch No.
                    3863 of April 30, 1935 concerning the export of arms to China, I have the honor
                    to transmit herewith copy and translation of a note dated May 2, 1935 from the
                    Federal Political Department<note n="63" xml:id="d732fn63">Not printed.</note>
                    concerning this matter.</p>
                <p>From this note it will be seen that the Political Department states that the
                    Federal authorities are at present studying the method of establishing legal
                    provisions for the strictest control of the export of arms and munitions from
                    Switzerland to foreign countries and that it states further that nothing
                    indicates the possibility that arms and munitions of war are being manufactured
                    in Switzerland for contraband shipment into Chinese territory.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Minister:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stanley Hawks</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Secretary of Legation</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
